'''appserver.io''' is an [[application server]] for [[PHP]] based web environments. The project consists of [[middleware]] which delivers classical PHP web applications and provides additional services.

==History==
The basic idea of a [[WildFly]] equivalent for PHP was present within TechDivision well before July 2013 when development on the project began, due to technical shortcomings of the PHP language .

At that time the possibility of a non-blocking, [[Network socket|socket]]-based PHP middleware was given by using an asynchronous event driven workflow or forked [[Process (computing)|processes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reactphp.org/|title=React|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://php.net/manual/en/function.pcntl-fork.php|title=PHP: pcntl_fork - Manual|publisher=}}</ref> In parallel, as of August 2012, a [[Thread (computing)|threading]] extension for PHP by Joe Watkins enabled true [[POSIX]] compatible multithreading.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pthreads.org/|title=pthreads - Share Nothing, Do Everything :)|publisher=}}</ref> Controversially<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://berb.github.io/diploma-thesis/original/043_threadsevents.html|title=4.3 The Case of Threads vs. Events|website=berb.github.io|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> threads were used because they allow the programmer to account for hardware usage instead of relying on the used runtime environment and enable easier communication between parallel working batches.

After deciding on the technical blueprint, development began on the [[GitHub]] platform. {{as of|2015}}, the project consisted of 36 separate [[Repository (version control)|repositories]], around 80,000 lines of code and estimated effort of 18 years ([[COCOMO]] model).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.openhub.net/p/appserver-io|title=The appserver.io Open Source Project on Open Hub|publisher=}}</ref>

==Licensing==
Appserver.io is [[open-source software]] under the [[Open Software License|OSL]] in version 3.0. It can be downloaded either as an installable package from the project page, or as a source from GitHub. The project aims at a [[freemium]] marketing approach splitting the software into a Community, Professional and an Enterprise Edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appserver.io/products/enterprise-edition.html|title=appserver.io enterprise edition|publisher=}}</ref> {{as of|2015}}, the Community Edition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appserver.io/products/community-edition.html|title=appserver.io community edition|publisher=}}</ref> contained all base features and is open source and free of charge.

{{as of|2015}}, the Professional Edition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appserver.io/products/professional-edition.html|title=appserver.io professional edition|publisher=}}</ref> could only be used within the [[Microsoft Azure]] cloud service and offers additional developer support.

==Product features==
Appserver.io includes a runtime environment, containing PHP extended with external libraries, PHP extensions and service daemons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/appserver-io-php/runtime/blob/master/build.default.properties|title=appserver-io-php/runtime|publisher=}}</ref> It is an out-of-the-box runtime environment for PHP development. The use of a multithreading environment is considered to break the so-called [[Shared nothing architecture|shared nothing]] concept of PHP as it allows for inter-process communication on object level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/PHP/comments/1jo517/multithreading_in_php_with_pthreads/|title=Multithreading in PHP with pthreads • /r/PHP|publisher=}}</ref>

Together with the bundled runtime, appserver.io bundles administration. As of version 0.6.0 application management is implemented with file-based application deployment.

Appserver.io offers [[servlet]]s, objects that persist between client requests. These can eliminate repeated bootstrapping of applications, but require the wrapping of bootstrap parts. Appserver.io offers an Enterprise Bean implementation similar to [[Enterprise JavaBeans|Enterprise Java Beans]] functionality.

Appserver.io offers modular services that can be used individually by internal and external applications.

Features:
* [https://github.com/appserver-io/webserver Webserver]
* [https://github.com/appserver-io/appserver Persistence Container]
* [https://github.com/appserver-io/appserver Message Queue]
* [https://github.com/appserver-io/appserver Servlet Engine]
* [[Aspect-oriented programming|AOP]] support
* [[Design by Contract]] support
* Annotation based [[Dependency injection|Dependency Injection]]
* Timer service
* Deployment API
* Integrated [[FastCGI]] client and backend
* Enterprise Beans similar to [[Enterprise JavaBeans|Enterprise Java Beans]]

Appserver.io allows component-based scalability. Services and servers (e.g. an [[Http|HTTP]] webserver) are adjustable in size and number based on an [[XML]] configuration file. Additional components can be configured for remote access, allowing for [[Distributed computing|distributed systems]] and component replication.

