'''Jing''' ({{zh|s=敬|t=敬|p=Jìng}}) is a concept in [[Chinese philosophy]] which is typically translated as "reverence." It is often used by [[Confucius]] in the term ''gōngjìng'' ({{zh|恭敬}}), meaning "respectful reverence". The Confucian notion of respect has been likened to the later, western [[Immanuel Kant#Moral philosophy|Kantian]] notion.<ref>Dillon, Robin S., "Respect", The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Fall 2010 Edition), Edward N. Zalta (ed.), URL = <http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/fall2010/entries/respect/></ref> For Confucians, ''jìng'' requires ''[[Yi (Confucianism)|yì]]'', or righteousness, and a proper observation of rituals (''[[Li (Confucian)|lǐ]]''). To have ''jìng'' is vitally important in the maintenance of ''[[xiào]]'', or filial piety.<ref>Richey, J. (2005). Confucius, in Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy. URL = <http://www.iep.utm.edu/confuciu/></ref><ref>Confucius. (1997). The Analects of Confucius. Chichung Huang, Trans. Oxford University Press: Oxford, p. 30-31</ref>
