{{Infobox Korean name | hangul = 룡곡서원 | hanja = 龍谷書院 | rr = Yonggok seowon | mr = Ryonggok sŏwŏn | context = north | image = | caption = }}
The '''Ryonggok Confucian Shrine and Academy''' is located in [[Mangyongdae-guyok]], [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]].<ref> {{cite journal |last=용곡서원|first= |last2= |first2=|date=August 2001 |script-title=ko:한국도안문양사전 |url=http://www.dbpia.co.kr/Article/2726288 |journal=한국도안문양사전 |publisher= 여강출판사|volume= |issue= |pages= |isbn= 978-89-89457-48-0 |accessdate=6 July 2014|language= Korean }}</ref> It is listed as a [[National Treasures of North Korea]].
==History== Built in 1656, the Shrine is located on the slopes of [[Mount Ryonggak]], about ten kilometers from Pyongyang. <ref name=Baldi> {{cite journal |last= Baldi|first=Ferdinando |date=November 2008 |title= FERDINANDO BALDI: TEN ZAN OU LA DRÔLE D'AVENTURE D'UNE SÉRIE B ITALO-NORD -CORÉENNE|trans-title=Ferdinando Baldi: TEN ZAN OR THE WEIRD ADVENTURE OF AN ITALO-NORTH KOREAN B MOVIE|url= http://www.editions-harmattan.fr/index.asp?navig=catalogue&obj=numero&no=27156&no_revue=132|language=French |journal= COMMENT PEUT-ON ÊTRE CORÉEN ? Tan'Gun n°2|location= |publisher=L'Harmattan |accessdate= }}</ref><ref name=blogspot> {{cite web |url=http://www.ojardias.blogspot.ca/ |language=French |title=Ten Zan, l'ultime mission (2/2) |last1=Ojardias |first1=Frederic |last2= |first2= |date=April 1, 2010 |website=www.ojardias.blogspot.ca |publisher=|quote=References the following magazine as cited:Tan'gun, COMMENT PEUT-ON ÊTRE CORÉEN ? |accessdate=July 7, 2014}} </ref> The Academy was damaged by fire in the early 1710s, and was rebuilt in 1713. <ref> {{cite book |last=Corfield |first=Justin |date=Jul 15, 2013 |title=Historical Dictionary of Pyongyang |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a46gFDWr3aMC&lpg=PA188&ots=MCk9knubph&dq=Ryonggok&pg=PA188#v=onepage&q=Ryonggok&f=false |location= |publisher=Anthem Press |page= 256|isbn=0857282344 |accessdate=August 31, 2014 }} </ref>
The Academy served as a private educational institution during the [[Ri Dynasty]]. The complex includes two quarters - an auditorium and a shrine. The buildings were constructed in a row on sloping land. The auditorium quarter include an east classroom and a west classroom. Behind the shrine is a pavilion with a calligraphic board hung under the eaves of the roof. <ref> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Ryonggok School |url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2011/201111/news19/20111119-09ee.html |newspaper=KCNA |location=Pyongyang |publisher=Korean Central News Agency |date= November 19, 2011|accessdate=August 31, 2011 }}</ref>
The complex is also known as the Ryonggok Auditorium. The main building is known as the Taesong Hall; it is the largest building on the complex. The Taesong Hall's roof has a windbreak board on each side, “a unique form, rare to be seen in other old architectures”. The Auditorium includes an outer door, a dormitory and an inner door. The outer door has a two storied gable roof. The first floor of the complex was used as an auditorium and the second floor was used as a lecture room. There are the eastern and western study rooms on the both sides of the inner court. <ref> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Ryonggok Auditorium, Heritage of National Culture |url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2007/200709/news09/28.htm |newspaper=KCNA |location=Pyongyang|publisher=Korean Central News Agency |date=September 27, 2007 |accessdate=December 11, 2014 }}</ref> A sign board bearing the school’s name hangs from the eaves of the shrine and a monument in the north western house explains that the school was built in 1713. <ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/history/?culture+2 |title= Ryonggok School |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 20, 2016 |website=Naenara |publisher= |access-date= March 22, 2016|quote=}}</ref>
==Media Portrayal== The Shrine is featured in film [[Ten Zan: The Ultimate Mission]].<ref name=Baldi/><ref name=blogspot/>
