'''Ulrich of Strasburg''' (c. 1225–1277)<ref>[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/dietrich-freiberg/ Dietrich of Freiberg (Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> was a German [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] theologian and [[scholastic philosopher]] from [[Strasbourg]], [[Alsace]]. A disciple of [[Albertus Magnus]], he is known for his ''Summa de Bono'', written 1265 to 1272.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/12354c.htm], [http://ptta.pl/pef/angielski/hasla/a/albertthegreat.pdf (PDF)]</ref>
==References== *[[Jorge J. E. Gracia]], Timothy B. Noone (2005), ''A Companion to Philosophy in the Middle Ages''
==Notes== {{Reflist}}
==External links== *{{BBKL|u/ulrich_v_str|band=12|autor= Thomas Gandlau |artikel= Ulrich von Straßburg, auch Ulrich Engelberti |spalten=898-900}}
{{Authority control}}
[[Category:1277 deaths]] [[Category:German Dominicans]] [[Category:Medieval German theologians]] [[Category:13th-century Roman Catholic theologians]] [[Category:Scholastic philosophers]] [[Category:Year of birth uncertain]] [[Category:German male non-fiction writers]] [[Category:Dominican theologians]] [[Category:People from Strasbourg]] [[Category:13th-century German writers]] [[Category:13th-century Latin writers]]

[[Image:Paul Tannery.jpg|thumb|Paul Tannery, early theoriser of a Pythagorean "unit-point atomism"]] According to some [[20th century philosophy|twentieth-century philosophers]],<ref>[[Paul Tannery]] (1887), ''Pour l'histoire de la science Hellène'' (Paris), and [[John Raven|J. E. Raven]] (1948), ''Pythagoreans and Eleatics'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), are the major purveyors of this view.</reF> '''unit-point atomism''' was the philosophy of the [[Pythagoreans]], a conscious repudiation of [[Parmenides]] and the [[Eleatics]]. It stated that atoms were infinitesimally small ("point") yet possessed corporeality. It was a predecessor of [[Democritus|Democritean]] [[atomism]]. Most recent students of [[presocratic philosophy]], such as [[:de:Kurt von Fritz|Kurt von Fritz]], [[Walter Burkert]], [[Gregory Vlastos]], [[Jonathan Barnes]], and Daniel W. Graham have rejected that any form of atomism can be applied to the early Pythagoreans (before [[Ecphantus of Syracuse]]).<ref>[[Gregory Vlastos]] and Daniel W. Graham (1996), ''Studies in Greek Philosophy: The Presocratics'' (Princeton: Princeton University Press), 257.</ref>
Unit-point atomism was invoked in order to make sense of a statement ascribed to [[Zeno of Elea]] in [[Plato|Plato's]] ''[[Parmenides (dialogue)|Parmenides]]'': "these writings of mine were meant to protect the arguments of Parmenides against those who make fun of him. . . My answer is addressed to the partisans of the many. . ."<ref>[[Jonathan Barnes]] (1982), ''The Presocratic Philosophers'' (London: Routledge), 232&ndash;33.</ref> The anti-Parmenidean pluralists were supposedly unit-point atomists whose philosophy was essentially a reaction against the Eleatics. This hypothesis, however, to explain [[Zeno's paradoxes]], has been thoroughly discredited.
